acter of colonial government and examines the cultural nationalism of Negritude as a multifaceted movement rooted in an alternative black public sphere. He argues that interwar France must be understood as an imperial nation-state—an integrated sociopolitical system that linked a parliamentary republic to an administrative empire. An interdisciplinary study of colonial modernity combining French history, colonial studies, and social theory, The French Imperial Nation-State will compel readers to revise conventional assumptions about the distinctions between republicanism and racism, metropolitan and colonial societies, and national and transnational processes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfricanszFrance. 0aBlack peoplexRace identityzAfrica, WestxHistoryy20th century. 0aBlack peoplexRace identityzCaribbean AreaxHistoryy20th century. 0aBlack peoplezFrance. 0aNationalismzAfrica, WestxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzCaribbean AreaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  a20th century, history, historical, world wars, humanism, imperialism, imperialists, colonialism, france, french, nation, colonies, public debate, west africa, government, governing, cultural nationalism, culture, sociopolitical systems, interdisciplinary, modernity, modernism, republicanism, racism, race, racial identity, caribbean, transnationalism, international, citizenship, administration.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226773858423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226773858/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles